<h1>2.4 Adjectives</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em>: add discussion?</p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>a</strong>
(adjective)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> a-s—mn- (adjective, singular,
masculine, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Adjectives in Greek decline in all three declensions, like nouns.
There are four basic groups in which a certain adjective can belong to,
based on criteria of how many endings an adjective has and into which
declension its masculine and neuter forms belong to, as presented by
<span class="citation" data-cites="waanders2013">Waanders (2013)</span>.
The feminine forms, if they exist, always belong to the 1st
declension.</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Adjectives with three endings; masculine and neuter follow the 2nd
declension. Here we also have adjectives where the ending is contracted
(from -εος and -οος). For example:
<ul>
<li>masc.nom.sg. ἀγαθός (agathós), gen.sg. ἀγαθοῦ (agathoû)
<em>good</em></li>
<li>fem.nom.sg. ἀγαθή (agathḗ), gen.sg. ἀγαθῆς (agathês)</li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. ἀγαθόν (agathón), gen.sg. ἀγαθοῦ (agathoû)</li>
<li>masc.nom.sg. ἀργύρ-εος (argúr-eos), contr. ἀργυρ-οῦς (arguroûs),
gen.sg. ἀργυροῦ (arguroû) <em>of silver</em></li>
<li>fem.nom.sg. ἀργύρ-εα (argúr-ea), contr. ἀργυρ-ᾶ (argurâ), gen.sg.
ἀργυρᾶ (argurâ)</li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. ἀργύρ-εον (argúr-eon), contr. ἀργυρ-οῦν (arguroûn),
gen.sg. ἀργυροῦ (arguroû)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Adjectives with three endings; masculine and neuter follow the 3rd
declension. For example:
<ul>
<li>masc.nom.sg. ἡδύς (hēdús), gen.sg. ἡδέος (hēdéos) <em>pleasant,
sweet</em></li>
<li>fem.nom.sg. ἡδεῖα (hēdeîa), gen.sg. ἡδείας (hēdeíās)</li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. ἡδύ (hēdú), gen.sg. ἡδέος (hēdéos)</li>
<li>masc.nom.sg. μέλας (mélas), gen.sg. μέλανος (mélanos) <em>black,
dark</em></li>
<li>fem.nom.sg. μέλαινα (mélaina), gen.sg. μελαίνης (melaínēs)</li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. μέλαν (mélan), gen.sg. μέλανος (mélanos)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Adjectives with two endings; following the 2nd declension. Two-form
adjectives use one form for both masculine and feminine
(i.e.&nbsp;non-neuter), and one for neuter. For example:
<ul>
<li>non-neut.nom.sg. ἄδικος (ádikos), gen.sg. ἀδίκου (adíkou)
<em>unjust</em></li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. ἄδικον (ádikon), gen.sg. ἀδίκου (adíkou)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Adjectives with two endings; following the 3rd declension. For
example:
<ul>
<li>non-neut.nom.sg. ἀληθής (alēthḗs), gen.sg. ἀληθοῦς (alēthoûs)
<em>true, real</em></li>
<li>neut.nom.sg. ἀληθές (alēthés), gen.sg. ἀληθοῦς (alēthoûs)</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
